What does a row mean?

It appears that each row is a unique firm id and case id combination. Some cases appear to involve multiple firms. Firm id here is OIB number (a tax identification number - for persons and legal entities)

Drop case duplicates

We are only interested in unique cases, so we will drop the duplicate cases. The number of rows decreases from 1,371,345 to 1,140,286.

data_nodupl <- data[!duplicated(data["case_id"]),]

Filter out bankruptcy-related, shortened proceedings cases only

If we filter out all bankruptcy-related cases, we get 35,247 unique cases. But we are interested in similar bankruptcy-related cases, not outliers - will exclude all except majority (shortened proceedings). We now have 27,586 unique cases.

data_bkpt_all <- data_nodupl %>%
  filter(category_types %in% c(21, 81, 90, 93, 94, 95, 96) &
          dispute_types %in% c(167, 294, 411, 426, 447, 448, 449, 451, 453))

data_bkpt <- data_nodupl %>%
  filter(category_types == 81 & 
          dispute_types == 411)

#for future reference/filtering:
category_types_bkpt <- c(21, 81, 90, 93, 94, 95, 96)
dispute_types_bkpt <- c(167, 294, 411, 426, 447, 448, 449, 451, 453)

Explore basic patterns

How many cases are still open? How is inflow and case duration changing?

We limit the cases to those beginning after Jan 2010, then group cases by month when they had begun. The dark gray area represents the number of cases that began in that month, while the part highlighted in red represents the number of cases that began in that quarter and still remain open.The finding makes sense: the more recent the case, the more likely that it is still open

data_nodupl %>%
  filter(y_beg >= 2010) %>%
  group_by(m_beg) %>%
  summarize(still_open_count = sum(still_open),
            all_count = n()) %>%
  ggplot() +
  geom_area(aes(m_beg, all_count), stat = "identity") +
  geom_area(aes(m_beg, still_open_count, fill = "red"), stat = "identity") +
  labs(title = "Inflow of all cases", x = "Month when case began", y = "Unique cases") +
  scale_fill_manual(name = "", values = "red", labels = "Still open as of May 2016\n(end of data)") +
  theme_evelina +
  scale_y_continuous(label = comma)

data_nodupl %>%
  filter(y_beg >= 2010 & court_type == "2") %>%
  group_by(m_beg) %>%
  summarize(still_open_count = sum(still_open),
            all_count = n()) %>%
  ggplot() +
  geom_area(aes(m_beg, all_count), stat = "identity") +
  geom_area(aes(m_beg, still_open_count, fill = "red"), stat = "identity") +
  labs(title = "Inflow of commercial cases", x = "Month when case began", y = "Unique cases") +
  scale_fill_manual(name = "", values = "red", labels = "Still open as of May 2016\n(end of data)") +
  theme_evelina +
  scale_y_continuous(label = comma)

data_bkpt %>%
  filter(y_beg >= 2010) %>%

Municipal courts deal with the highest number of cases. High commercial and supreme courts deal with less than 0.1% of all cases in the data. Only type 2 (commercial) courts deal with commercial and bankruptcy-related cases

#drop the label in case R misbehaves
#var_label(data_nodupl$court_type) <- NULL

data_nodupl %>% 
  mutate(court_type = to_factor(court_type)) %>%
  count(court_type) %>% 
  arrange(desc(n)) %>% 
  mutate(court_type = as.character(court_type)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x="", y = n, fill = court_type)) +
  geom_bar(width = 1, stat = "identity") +
  coord_polar("y", start = 0) +
  theme_evelina +
  scale_y_continuous(label = comma)

Decision and procedure types There are 318 decision types across all resolved cases, 25 across bankruptcy-related cases.

data_nodupl %>% 
  filter(still_open == 0) %>%
  mutate(decision_types = to_factor(decision_types),
         decision_types = fct_lump(decision_types, n = 9)) %>%
  count(decision_types) %>% 
  mutate(decision_types = fct_explicit_na(decision_types, na_level = "Missing"),
         decision_types = fct_reorder(decision_types, n)) %>%
  ggplot() +
  geom_bar(aes(decision_types, n), stat = "identity") +
  coord_flip() +
  theme_evelina +
  scale_y_continuous(label = comma) +
  labs(x = "", y = "\nNumber of resolved cases", title = "The most popular decision\ntypes for resolved cases")

Status What is the difference between closed and archived and resolved? What does changed register vs.transferred mean?

data_nodupl %>%
  filter(y_beg >= 2010) %>%
  mutate(status = to_factor(status),
         status = fct_lump(status, n = 5)) %>%
  ggplot() +
  geom_bar(aes(m_beg, fill = status)) +
  theme_evelina +
  labs(title = "Count of cases by status", y = "Number of cases", x = "Month when case opened") +

It might be safer to use the IDs, not names then.

Only 132 judges have worked on bankruptcy-related cases, shortened proceedings. As bankruptcy-related cases inflow surged in the wake of the 2015 Bankruptcy Act, more unique judges had bankruptcy-related cases assigned to them - a perfectly intuitive result.

data_bkpt %>% 
  count(m_beg, assign_judge_id) %>%
  count(m_beg) %>%
  ggplot() +
  geom_line(aes(m_beg, n, group = 1)) +
  theme_evelina +
  labs(title = "Number of judges that had bankruptcy-related\ncases assigned to them",
       x = "\nMonth when case began", y = "Unique judges") +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = c(611, 675),
                   labels = c("Jan 2011", "April 2016")) +
  geom_vline(aes(xintercept = 668, linetype = "dashed"), color = "red") +
  scale_linetype_manual(name = "", 
                        values = "dashed", labels = "Month of 2015 Bankruptcy Act")
